commentary.Commentary: Coming up on Thursday - Just four games remain in the group stage, three of which are scheduled for 19th February. With all Super 8 spots sealed and the seedings pre-decided, there isn't much at stake for the qualified teams. However, for those heading home after the group stage, it's a chance to bow out on a high, especially for the Associate nations. First up on 19th February, the West Indies take on Italy in Kolkata. That will be followed by Sri Lanka facing Zimbabwe in Colombo, before Afghanistan round off the day’s action against Canada in Chennai. The first game of the day will commence at 5.30 am GMT. As always, you can join us early for all the build-up. Until then, take care and goodbye!

Super 8 spots locked in - Coming into Wednesday's triple-header, there was just one spot left up for grabs, and Pakistan sealed it with a convincing win over Namibia in Colombo. Earlier in the day in Delhi, South Africa brushed aside the UAE to make it four wins from four, while India followed suit to complete a perfect run through the group stage.

We have ticked a lot of boxes - The Indian skipper, Suryakumar Yadav says that there was a bit of dew around, which made things slightly challenging for the bowlers, but overall, he is very happy with the performance. He acknowledges that they could find themselves in similar situations again, such as losing early wickets, but stresses that it is important for the batters to understand their responsibilities. Speaking about Dube, he recalls his knock in Vizag against New Zealand, mentioning that he wanted the Player of the Match award that day as well. Says that it was an amazing effort from Dube to help India reach 193. He feels the team has ticked a lot of boxes and adds that even in victory, there are lessons to be learned. On India’s bowling options, he describes it as a good headache to have, with plenty of variety at their disposal. He concludes by saying he is happy with how things are progressing, highlighting that contributions are coming from everyone.

We failed to make the key moments count - The captain of Netherlands, Scott Edwards says that they started really well. Adds that Aryan Dutt has been amazing for them, especially bowling in the Powerplay. Mentions that they know India has the firepower, and they were in the game as well, but a couple of missed chances and some misexcution costed them. Says that they had a few wickets in hand towards the end and took the bowlers down. Edwards shares that any time you come to India, you learn a lot. Smaller grounds, flatter wickets, and large crowds with so much hype. He believes that they did not play to their potential in this World Cup, did well in patches, but failed to make the key moments count.
Time for the presentation ceremony...

Dube's blitz powered India to 193 - Earlier, after opting to bat first, India suffered an early setback as Abhishek Sharma registered his third duck of the World Cup. Aryan Dutt was outstanding in the Powerplay, delivering three tight overs that set the tone. His effort was well supported through the middle phase, keeping India in check until Shivam Dube's arrival shifted the complexion of the game. Dube's blistering 31-ball 66, his T20I career-best score, powered India to 193, with the Dutch conceding 75 runs in the final five overs.

Dutch hung in, but never took charge - Jasprit Bumrah had the ball on a string, and Max O'Dowd looked all at sea against him. If Bumrah didn't get him, Varun Chakaravarthy did. There wasn't much separating the two sides at the end of 12 overs. In fact, the Dutch were slightly ahead at 94 for the loss of one less wicket, compared to India's 89 at the same stage. But the bigger question was - who could produce an innings like Shivam Dube’s? And could they do it against the likes of Bumrah, Varun and Arshdeep? The trio did not complete their full quota of overs, with Hardik Pandya and Dube given a longer run instead. While they were carted around, no one from the Netherlands truly took the attack to the opposition or seriously threatened to pull off the chase.

PLAYER OF THE MATCH - Shivam Dube wins the award for his impactful knock of 66 runs from 31 balls. He also chipped in with a couple of wickets but was on the expensive side. Dube says that the wicket was a bit tough, but he enjoyed batting on it. Adds that there was some pressure, the off-spinner bowled well with four dot balls, but he knew he could make it up later on. Dube shares that he loves hitting sixes, but sometimes the situation demands something different, and he has to look for boundaries as well. Tells that the skipper and coach have given him the freedom to bat wth a higher strike rate, but in this game, he had to take a bit of time. On his bowling, Dube says that he is working hard on it, and the results are showing as well. He feels that in a T20 game, you will get hit but also pick up wickets.

India make it four in four - Not a perfect performance, but one that gets the job done. For all the talk of them being strong favourites coming into the tournament, Suryakumar Yadav's side hasn't quite hit top gear yet, but they continue to find ways to win. They will know there is plenty to improve on in different aspects of their game. The Netherlands fought hard until the very end while chasing, but never quite threatened to get over the line. They bowled well for large parts, only to lose their way at the death. They head home with a solitary win, left to ponder what might have been.

It goes high in the air over extra cover. SKY runs backwards and calls for it, while Rinku Singh comes forward from long off. Suryakumar Yadav circles around it but fails to settle under it and the ball hits his chest and falls out. Good thing they avoided the collision here. Two taken.

The Netherlands are not going to go down without a fight. This is a big call from Suryakumar Yadav. Arshdeep Singh and Jasprit Bumrah both have one over left, but he has gone with Shivam Dube. Perhaps the Indian skipper wants to see how Dube fares if a similar scenario presents itself in the Super 8 stage.

DRINKS! India get a key breakthrough right at the stroke of Drinks. Netherlands are right up there where India were at the same stage, but they will need someone to do a Shivam Dube. Bas de Leede looked good but he got out at the wrong time for them and now the responsibility shifts to the captain, Scott Edwards. India have experimented through Shivam Dube and Abhishek Sharma but they have been expensive despite Dube picking up that wicket. Now, they will look to bring back the frontline bowlers and close this game out. Here is Washington Sundar to bowl after the break.

OUT! CAUGHT! Shivam Dube lets out a sigh of relief. The ploy to bowl full and wide finally brings about success for Dube. Bas shuffles across the stumps to make contact. He goes hard on the drive but the ball comes off a thickish outside edge. It goes flat to short third, where Varun Chakaravarthy is a bit fine on the edge of the ring. He hops and takes a sharp catch around his waist. Netherlands' chances in the chase take a big dent.

commentary.Commentary: On a length and on off, Michael Levitt steers it away through point for a run. 50 comes up for Netherlands!

commentary.Default_Commentary: 7.2: Hardik Pandya to Michael Levitt, Four!
commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Fine shot! Hardik Pandya bowls the slower one but serves this too full, outside off. Michael Levitt stays leg side of the ball, gets low and waits for it before smacking it through covers for a boundary.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 7.1: Hardik Pandya to Bas de Leede, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Back of a length and around off, Bas de Leede steps across and punches it to long off for a single.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 6.6: Washington Sundar to Bas de Leede, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Shortish delivery, on off, Bas de Leede waits for it and chips it towards long on for one more.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 6.5: Washington Sundar to Michael Levitt, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Drags his length back, on middle, Michael Levitt moves back and flicks it to deep mid-wicket for one.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 6.4: Washington Sundar to Bas de Leede, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Floated, full and on off, turns in, Bas de Leede eases it to long on for a run.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 6.3: Washington Sundar to Michael Levitt, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Tossed up nicely, full and on middle, Michael Levitt taps it away towards backward point for a quick single.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 6.2: Washington Sundar to Michael Levitt, Four!
commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Gets it away! Washington Sundar bowls this flatter, short again and angling into the leg side. Michael Levitt backs away, goes down on one knee and swipes it away to the deep backward square leg fence for a boundary.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 6.1: Washington Sundar to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Shorter in length and on off, Michael Levitt backs away and punches it to short cover.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 5.6: Varun Chakaravarthy to Bas de Leede, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Touch slower through the air, full and on middle, turns in again. Bas de Leede fails to read it and tries to work it across the line but misses and gets hit on the pads. Netherlands are 36/1 at the end of the Powerplay!
Suryakumar Yadav has positioned himself at slip.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 5.6: Varun Chakaravarthy to Bas de Leede, Wide!
commentary.Commentary: WIDE! Quicker and shorter but down the leg side, Bas de Leede fails to glance it away. Wided.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 5.5: Varun Chakaravarthy to Bas de Leede, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Another wrong 'un, full and on off, spins in. Bas de Leede gets stuck in his crease and tries to play it but gets an inside edge onto his pads. That saves him there.

With the fall of Max O'Dowd, it is time for a DRINKS BREAK. After a thorough interrogation by Jasprit Bumrah, another challenge awaits the Dutch in the form of Varun Chakaravarthy. The required run rate has already climbed to 11, and it will be crucial for the Netherlands to keep the scoreboard ticking. Even if the boundaries don't come regularly, rotating the strike with ones and twos and picking the right options to target will be key. Bas de Leede walks out at number 3.

OUT! CASTLED! Varun Chakaravarthy keeps picking up wickets in this World Cup. He fires this one full and on middle, turns in as this is the googly. Max O'Dowd makes room and has a big hoick across the line but plays all over it. The ball goes through and uproots the leg stump out of the ground. Netherlands are 35/1, chasing 194 runs.
commentary.Default_Commentary: 5.4: Varun Chakaravarthy to Max O'Dowd, OUT! b Varun Chakaravarthy.
5.3: Varun Chakaravarthy to Max O'Dowd, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Pushed through quicker, short and on middle and leg, angling in. Max O'Dowd misses his flick and gets hit on the pads.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 5.2: Varun Chakaravarthy to Michael Levitt, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Flatter, shortish and on middle, Michael Levitt backs away to cut but gets a bottom edge towards short third for a run.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 5.1: Varun Chakaravarthy to Max O'Dowd, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Flighted, full and around off, Max O'Dowd looks to drive it away but gets an inside edge through square leg for a single.
Spin from both ends. Varun Chakaravarthy has been introduced into the attack now.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 4.6: Washington Sundar to Max O'Dowd, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Slower but the length stays short, on middle. Max checks his shot and punches it a bit uppishly to long on for a run. 11 runs off Sundar's first over on his return to the side.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 4.5: Washington Sundar to Max O'Dowd, 2 runs.
commentary.Commentary: Sundar keeps it on the shorter side, following the batter, Max manages to get it away as he pulls it wide of deep mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 4.4: Washington Sundar to Max O'Dowd, Six!
commentary.Commentary: SIX! First biggie of the chase. This will give Max O'Dowd some confidence. Sundar spots Max backing away and he follows him with a ball bowled into the surface. O'Dowd manages to get inside the line and pulls it over backward square leg for a six.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 4.3: Washington Sundar to Michael Levitt, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Fractionally short, on middle, Levitt pulls it in front of square leg for a single.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 4.2: Washington Sundar to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Flat and short, around middle and leg. Levitt steps out early and then adjusts by tapping it to mid-wicket.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 4.1: Washington Sundar to Max O'Dowd, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Pushes it through first up, short and on off, Max punches it to long on for a single.
Will Arshdeep Singh get a third over? No, time for spin now as Washington Sundar replaces Arshdeep.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 3.6: Jasprit Bumrah to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Bumrah probably spotted Levitt taking a couple of steps down the track. He responds by taking the pace off, on a length, on off. Michael can only pat it down on the strip.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 3.5: Jasprit Bumrah to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Bumrah tries to bring the ball back in but sprays it on the pads. Levitt misses out on the half-volley and gets rapped on the front pad.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 3.4: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Fuller and curving away slightly, Max stays rooted to the crease and goes hard on the drive as he looks to force it down the ground. Gets a thickish outside edge which goes down to deep third. They cross.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 3.3: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Hits the top of off, does Bumrah, Max hops and dabs it to backward point.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 3.2: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, No run.
commentary.Commentary: The interrogation continues for Max O'Dowd! Angled in and then moving away off the deck, around the off stump. Max goes searching for the ball and just hangs his bat out. Gets beaten all ends up on the outside edge.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 3.1: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, Four!
commentary.Commentary: DROPPED, FOUR! Abhishek Sharma is back on the field and straight away in the action. Angled in, on a good length, on off. Max pushes out in front of his body with hard hands and gets an outside edge. Sharma is standing at a wide slip and he dives across to his left. He goes for the catch with his left hand, but the ball does not stick. It hits his palm before going behind to the fence.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 2.6: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, Four!
commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Flayed away! A bit too wide, on a back of a length. Levitt cashes in on the width as he slaps it over the leaping backward point fielder for a four.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 2.5: Arshdeep Singh to Max O'Dowd, Leg bye.
commentary.Commentary: Leg bye! Around the hips, on a short of a length, O'Dowd fails to get it away. A leg bye is taken as the ball goes off the pads to short fine leg.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 2.4: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, 1 run.
commentary.Commentary: Mishit but safe! On a short of a length, on middle. Levitt has a swipe across the line and the bat turns in his hands. He mistimes it uppishly towards mid on, where Washington Sundar runs around the ball rather than running at the ball. He moves to his right and collects it on the bounce. They cross.
Abhishek Sharma is off the field. Axar Patel is the substitute fielder for him.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 2.3: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Dug in short, on off, Michael ducks under it.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 2.2: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Nearly went to hand! On a nagging length, on middle, Levitt makes room to go through the off side. He opens the bat face to use the pace of the ball. It almost carries to the sub fielder, Axar Patel, who is standing at a wide slip. Axar dives to his left and manages to make the stop.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 2.1: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Across off, on a short of a length. Levitt stands tall on his toes to punch it away, but the ball comes on slower than he anticipated. Ekes out an inside edge onto the pads.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 1.6: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, No run.
commentary.Commentary: On top of off, on a back of a length, Max watchfully stabs it down on the off side. End of a probing first over from Bumrah.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 1.5: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, No run.
commentary.Commentary: This goes away from the right-hander after pitching, on a good length, around the off stump. Max looks to cover the line with a straight bat but misses.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 1.4: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Well dug out! Tailing back in, right in the blockhole, on off and middle. O'Dowd keeps his front pad out of the firing line and drops his bat down on the ball.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 1.3: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Coming back into the right-hander, on a length, Max does not move his feet at all and swishes at it. He is beaten on the inside edge.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 1.2: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, Four!
commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Max O'Dowd is off the mark with an edgy boundary. In the corridor, on a good length. O'Dowd fiddles at the delivery well away from his body. Gets an outside edge that goes well wide of the man at first slip and fine of the deep third fielder.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 1.1: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, No run.
commentary.Commentary: An absolute ripper! Angled into the right-hander, on a good length, Max looks to defend it right under his eyes and brings his bat out in front. The ball threatens to angle in but then holds its line to zip past the outside edge and the bounce takes it over the stumps.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 1.1: Jasprit Bumrah to Max O'Dowd, Wide!
commentary.Commentary: Wide! A wayward start from Bumrah. Slips it down leg, on a length, Max misses out on the tickle.
Jasprit Bumrah to bowl from the other end.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 0.6: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Arshdeep sticks to the short ball, around off, Levitt takes a couple of steps down the track and glides it with an open bat face. He picks out the man at short third. A couple of yards to the left or right and it would have been a boundary.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 0.5: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Another short ball, around the right shoulder. Levitt drops his wrists and sways away from the line of the ball.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 0.4: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Decking away on a hard length, around off, Levitt has a big swing across the line but the ball keeps rising and goes over his blade.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 0.3: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, 2 runs.
commentary.Commentary: Looked like the attempted outswinger from Arshdeep but the line is too straight. Full and on the pads. Michael clips it between mid-wicket an d mid on for a couple of runs. Washington Sundar gives chase and hauls it in.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 0.2: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, Four!
commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Lovely shot and Michael Levitt is underway, so are Netherlands! A better line, on middle but the length is a bit too full. Levitt shows the full face of the blade and knocks it all along the ground to the right of mid off for the first boundary.

commentary.Default_Commentary: 0.1: Arshdeep Singh to Michael Levitt, No run.
commentary.Commentary: Rapped on the pads! A prolonged appeal from Arshdeep Singh but it seems to be doing too much. Suryakumar Yadav has a word with Ishan Kishan and eventually decides against the review. That may have even pitched outside the line. Hooping back in, full and on leg. Levitt steps out to counter the swing and attempts the flick but is beaten on the inside edge and gets hit on the front pad. Well, the Ball Tracking later shows it was pitching down the leg side. Good thing India did not review it.
